Ranunculus hispidus is a species of flowering plant in the buttercup family (Ranunculaceae).
Its stem and leaves are covered in long, stiff, white hairs, giving it a bristly appearance. 
The flowers are typically bright yellow with five petals and numerous stamens. 
The petals are shiny and have a delicate, papery texture. 
Ranunculus hispidus can be found growing in wet habitats such as marshes, meadows, and along streams. 
It is native to North America, and can be found in many regions of the United States and Canada. 
The plant is also known by a number of common names, including hispid buttercup, bristly buttercup, and swamp buttercup.
